<div id="review_1489715296" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1489715296" />
    <a title="Edward" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12933866-edward"><img alt="Edward" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1444136022p2/12933866.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1489715296?book_show_action=true">Nov 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edward" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edward" href="/user/show/12933866-edward">Edward</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12933866-edward?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12933866-edward?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1489715296" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15848482786810557485"><i>Einstein&apos;s Dreams</i> is a very light, slight novel. The tone and structure are almost exactly those of Calvino&apos;s <i>Invisible Cities</i>, and the spirit is pure Borges. Each story is a variation on the theme of time, and each world is so lightly sketched as to represent nothing more than a passing thought; one cannot dwell too much on the implications of each of these thought-experiments. Instead the novel (like Calvino&apos;s) leads us to recognise the Venice of our own experience, refracted in these many wor</span>
  <span id="freeText15848482786810557485" style="display:none"><i>Einstein's Dreams</i> is a very light, slight novel. The tone and structure are almost exactly those of Calvino's <i>Invisible Cities</i>, and the spirit is pure Borges. Each story is a variation on the theme of time, and each world is so lightly sketched as to represent nothing more than a passing thought; one cannot dwell too much on the implications of each of these thought-experiments. Instead the novel (like Calvino's) leads us to recognise the Venice of our own experience, refracted in these many worlds.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15848482786810557485" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1489715296">
